  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA82">
<l>paṭaiyārum vāṭkaṇṇār pāracināṭ paimpūn</l>
<l>toṭaiyalō ṭēntiya tūpa – miṭaiyiṭaiyiṉ</l>
<l>mīṉmāya mācūṇum vēṅkaṭamē mēlorunāṇ</l>
<l>māṉmāya veytāṉ varai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Vēṅkaṭam, that magically absorbs stains<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here mācūṇum appears to be an isolated form not known to the TL. Tārkkatīrttar Rāmānujācāryar glosses with aḻukkaṭaiyum paṇṇāniṟkum. Morphologically it looks like a peyareccam based on the root noun ūṇ, “eating”, instead of the verb uṇṇutal. Can it be “stain-absorbing” = sin-absorbing? There is a parallel in TVM 1.5.4: maṉam cey ñāṉatt* uṉ perumai mācu-uṇāt*-ō māyōṉ-ē, “Will not your greatness of mind-made knowledge absorb [all] flaw, Dark one?”</note>, so that the stars vanish</l>
<l>in between the incense offered together with strands of fresh flowers</l>
<l>on the twelveth day by those with sword eyes that they wear as weapons<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">vāḷ kaṇṇār is a standard poetic description of women and simply seems to refer to female devotees here, presumably unmarried, although such a thing does not seem to be mentioned elsewhere in the Antāti-s. The description contains further details, such as the specification of the 12th day, that seem to allude to a particular ritual occasion, but it is not clear which it could be.</note>,</l> 
<l>is the mountain of him who on a former day took aim with great magic.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
